 Hybrid Identities of Mixed-Ethnic Girls in Japan -- t15 Singlish and Hybridity: The Dialogic of Outer-Circle Teacher Identities -- t16 Enacting Hybridity in the Philippine Diaspora -- t17 Reframing the Global-Local Dialectic and Hybridized Textual Practices -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe chapters in this volume seek to bring hybrid language practices to the center of discussions about English as a global language. They demonstrate how local linguistic resources and practices are involved in the refashioning of identities in a variety of cross-cultural and geographical contexts, and illustrate hybridity as an enactment of resistance and creativity. Drawing on a variety of disciplines and ideological perspectives, the authors use contexts as diverse as social media, Bollywood films, workplaces and kindergartens to explore the ways in which English has become a part of localities and social relations in ways that are of significant sociolinguistic interest in understanding the dynamics of mobile cultures and transcultural flows.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnglish languagexGlobalization. 0aEnglish languagexStandardization. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 0aEnglish languagezForeign countries. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh1 aAlsagoff, Lubna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlsagoff, Lubna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBhatt, Rakesh M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Ofelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular